# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>Named for the iconic gauntlet on the Lyran Commonwealth's insignia, the Gauntlet is a fifty-five-ton OmniMech manufactured by Coventry Metal Works for the Lyran Commonwealth Armed Forces. The design traces its origins to a proposal by Archon Adam Steiner for a medium-weight OmniMech embodying the Lyran military spirit. Coventry Metal Works acquired the plans for the Bushwacker from TharHes Industries in the aftermath of the Jihad, using them as the foundation for an entirely new OmniMech platform.</p><p>The Gauntlet endured a lengthy development cycle before finally entering service in 3128, nearly thirty years after the original proposal. Initially overlooked by elite commands, the design found its warmest reception among regular line units and lightning companies throughout the LCAF.</p>
capabilities:<p>Coventry Metal Works produced a solid cavalry OmniMech built around a Defiance 275 light fusion engine and a Coventry GTL-Flex endo steel frame. The inclusion of built-in MASC allows the Gauntlet to achieve burst speeds exceeding one hundred kilometers per hour, enabling it to keep pace with lighter 'Mechs during rapid maneuvers. Ten double heat sinks manage thermal output, while Lexington Limited light ferro-fibrous armor provides reasonable protection without excessive weight. The chassis offers twenty-one tons of pod space, providing significant flexibility for mission-specific loadouts.</p><p>The Primary configuration is geared toward longer-range engagements in open terrain, mounting a heavy PPC as its principal weapon supported by a Thunderbolt 10 launcher with two tons of CASE-protected ammunition. A pod-mounted supercharger further augments the Gauntlet's already impressive MASC-enhanced speed. The Alternate Configuration A pairs MML-7 launchers with light PPCs for flexible combined-arms fire, while the B configuration draws inspiration from the Black Hawk-KU and Clan Nova, packing ten medium lasers and a medium pulse laser linked to a targeting computer alongside jump jets and a coolant pod. Cyclops-manufactured communications and targeting systems complete the electronics suite, providing reliable battlefield awareness across all configurations.</p>
deployment:<p>Alternate Configuration A leverages the versatility of multi-missile launchers paired with energy weapons for flexible combined-arms warfare. Twin MML-7 launchers mounted in the side torsos allow MechWarriors to switch between long-range LRM and short-range SRM ammunition as tactical conditions demand, while a pair of light PPCs in each arm provide supplementary fire at medium to long range. CASE II installed in both arms shields the weaponry from potential ammunition explosions, reflecting the careful engineering that went into this configuration's survivability.</p>
history:<p>The genesis of the Gauntlet lies in the convergence of two events during the Jihad era: Archon Adam Steiner's vision for a uniquely Lyran medium OmniMech, and TharHes Industries' desperate need for capital after Word of Blake forces devastated their production facilities on Tharkad. Coventry Metal Works purchased the Bushwacker's plans and began development of what would become the Gauntlet, though the project would face nearly three decades of setbacks before reaching production.</p><p>Technical challenges plagued the early development period, compounded by active opposition from within the LCAF's senior leadership. Many Social Generals viewed a medium-weight OmniMech as beneath the Lyran military tradition of fielding heavier designs and resisted allocating resources to the project. It was only the weight of the late Archon Steiner's legacy that prevented the program's outright cancellation. The Gauntlet finally entered service with the LCAF in 3128, with one of the first production models presented to the Second Donegal Guards in honor of their thousandth anniversary.</p><p>The disdain from LCAF High Command paradoxically benefited the Gauntlet's operational deployment. Commanders of prestigious regiments, typically first in line for new OmniMech designs, declined to requisition the Gauntlet. As a result, the design percolated down to medium companies and regular line formations throughout the LCAF, particularly the lightning companies where its speed and flexibility were welcomed enthusiastically. Despite the senior leadership's reluctance to challenge the late Archon's wish that the Gauntlet remain an exclusively Lyran design, the 'Mech has never been offered for foreign sale.</p><p>The Gauntlet saw notable action during the Jade Falcon invasion of Arcturus in 3142, when the Fifteenth Arcturan Guards deployed a lance of Gauntlets in their lightning company against the Clan assault. The regiment was overwhelmed but the Gauntlets proved critical to the rearguard, running down light Falcon 'Mechs that had slipped past screening elements. During the invasion of Uhuru at the start of Operation HAMMERFALL, the Fourth Lyran Regulars employed their Gauntlets at the forefront of engagements against the Thirteenth Atrean Hussars, using them as bait before switching to close-range configurations to devastating effect. The design's shared components with the Bushwacker continue to benefit both manufacturers through economies of scale, ensuring the Gauntlet's production remains viable despite its limited export market.</p>
